<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[332,1263,392,1737]" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">
Like the previous species, this pentatomid was also found in small numbers on privet. No nymphs and eggs were observed on this plant. This pentatomid inhabits much of northern South America (CALLAN, 1948), but it seems to be more typical of West Indies and Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="VAN DUZEE, E. P." box="[720,912,833,857]" journalOrPublisher="Trans. Am. ent. Soc., Washington" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 80" part="30" refId="ref7017" refString="VAN DUZEE, E. P. 1904. Annotated list of the Pentatomidae recorded from America North of Mexico, with descriptions of some new species. Trans. Am. ent. Soc., Washington, 30: 1 - 80." title="Annotated list of the Pentatomidae recorded from America North of Mexico, with descriptions of some new species" type="journal article" year="1904">VAN DUZEE, 1904</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="WALDBAUER, G. P." box="[933,1137,833,857]" journalOrPublisher="Anais Soc. ent. Brasil, Jaboticabal" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" pagination="223 - 229" part="6" refId="ref7062" refString="WALDBAUER, G. P. 1977. Damage to soybean seeds by South American stink bugs. Anais Soc. ent. Brasil, Jaboticabal, 6 (2): 223 - 229." title="Damage to soybean seeds by South American stink bugs" type="journal article" year="1977">WALDBAUER (1977)</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1794" class="Insecta" family="Pentatomidae" genus="Thyanta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perditor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">T. perditor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an important pest of soybean in Colombia. In Brazil, it also feeds on soybean, and on wheat, 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="L." box="[490,666,892,916]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Bidens" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[490,636,892,916]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">Bidens pilosa</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
being its preferred wild host (
<bibRefCitation author="PANIZZI, A. R. &amp; HERZOG, D. C." box="[989,1250,892,916]" journalOrPublisher="Ann. ent. Soc. Am., Washington" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" pagination="646 - 650" part="77" refId="ref6617" refString="PANIZZI, A. R., &amp; HERZOG, D. C. 1984. Biology of Thyanta perditor. Ann. ent. Soc. Am., Washington, 77 (6): 646 - 650." title="Biology of Thyanta perditor" type="journal article" year="1984">PANIZZI &amp; HERZOG, 1984</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[332,1263,392,1737]" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">
Adults greenish with a red band on pronotum. Females 12.0 mm (n = 5) long, and males 11.0 mm (n = 5). Early instars oval and lightbrown to black. Later instars black with white or yellowish spots on abdomen (
<bibRefCitation author="GRAZIA, J. &amp; VECCHIO, M. C. &amp; DEL &amp; HILDEBRAND, R." box="[745,957,979,1004]" journalOrPublisher="Anais Soc. ent. Brasil, Jaboticabal" pageId="11" pageNumber="32" pagination="261 - 268" part="11" refId="ref6286" refString="GRAZIA, J.; VECCHIO, M. C. DEL &amp; HILDEBRAND, R. 1982. Estudo das ninfas de pentatomideos (Heteroptera) que vivem sobre soja (Glycine max (L.) Merrill): IV - Acrosternum impicticorne (Stal, 1872). Anais Soc. ent. Brasil, Jaboticabal, 11 (2): 261 - 268." title="Estudo das ninfas de pentatomideos (Heteroptera) que vivem sobre soja (Glycine max (L.) Merrill): IV - Acrosternum impicticorne (Stal, 1872)" type="journal article" year="1982">
GRAZIA 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,884,980,1004]" pageId="11" pageNumber="32">et al.</emphasis>
, 1982
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
